## Play-by-Play Implementation Steps

### 1. Remove Hardcoded Credentials
- Locate any hardcoded Google Client ID or Client Secret in the codebase  
- Replace them with environment variables  

---

### 2. Set Up Environment Variables

Create a `.env` file in the project root:

```env
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your_client_secret
GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI=http://localhost:8000/auth/callback


### 3. Create .env.example

Add a template file to the repository:

GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=
GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI=

- Do NOT include real credentials
- Commit this file so future developers know what is required

###  4. Configure OAuth in Google Cloud Console


- Use a shared team project (not personal accounts) in Google Cloud Console
- Add authorized redirect URIs:
- http://localhost:8000/auth/callback
- Production URL (if applicable)

 
###  5. Standardize Redirect URIs

- Ensure the application reads GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI from .env
- Remove any hardcoded redirect URLs from the code


### 6. Auto-Load Environment Variables

- Use dotenv or equivalent package
- Ensure .env is automatically loaded when the app starts
- No manual export steps required

### 7. Document Setup for Future Developers

New developer setup steps:

- Clone the repository
- Copy .env.example → .env
- Add shared credentials
- Run the application


### 8. Test From Scratch

- Delete local .env
- Clone repository fresh
- Follow only the documented setup steps
- Confirm Google login works without any manual fixes
